Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

4) The average cost for the weekend is slightly higher than on weekdays possibly due to the high count received on weekends.

df_rated = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given'].copy() # create new dataframe with 'Not given' values in rating column filtered out.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [63]:
compute_rev = 0
for i in df['cost_of_the_order']:
    if i > 20:
        compute_rev = compute_rev + (0.25 * i) # multiply orders greater than 20 dollars by 25%
    elif 5 < i < 20:
        compute_rev = compute_rev + (0.15 * i) # multiply orders greater than 5 dollars but less than 20 dollars by 15%
    
print("{:.2f}".format(compute_rev)) # print result to two decimal places.

6166.30

Observations:¶

The total revenue generated by the company across all the orders is 6166.30 dollars

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

In [65]:
df['total_time'] = df['food_preparation_time'] + df['delivery_time'] #create column consisting total time for both conditions.

prep_count = df['total_time'].count()  #number of rows in the total time column

prep_over_60 = df['total_time'][df['total_time']> 60].count() #number of rows with values over 60

percent_prep = (prep_over_60 / prep_count) * 100 #divide both rows and multiply by 100

print(round(percent_prep,2))

10.54

Observations:¶

Observations: About 10.5% of orders take more than 60 minutes to be prepared and delivered.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • The weekend period received more orders than the weekdays possibly because there is generally more or gatherings on the weekend than on the weekday.
  • The data showed a fairly consistent food preparation time for the various cuisines. However, the varied delivery times significantly impacted the overall time it took to complete an order (from order receipt to delivery).
  • There are a varied number of cuisines to reach a diverse market. However, some cuisines were more popular amongst the customers than others. 10 cuisines did not record orders greater than 100.
  • Also, the distribution of restaurants were biased towards a few. Some restaurants received more orders than others. This could be due to food quality, general popularity in the market or a certain demographic, etc. Further investigation could be done to learn more.
  • Delivery time was generally shorter on weekends than on weekdays perhaps due to less traffic on delivery routes or fewer delivery agents available on weekdays.
  • The customer behavior calculated the ratio of order id to customer id. This aimed to show the average number of times a customer placed an order. A result less than 2 indicates that there were a significant number of customers that made orders only once.
  • Even though a significant number of orders received rating of 5, 38% of orders did not receive ratings. This is a significant number and could have impacted the overall rating distribution if available.
  • The ratings were not influenced by the food preparation time, delivery time or the cost of the orders. Customers possibly rated based on other priorities like taste, quality of service, etc.
  • There are no extraordinarily high prices for the menus. However, the mean price is quite biased towards the cheaper side perhaps giving an insight into the nature of the customer base or the demographic distribution. Perhaps orders originate more from students who are likely to purchase relatively cheaper meals.
  • The cost of the order does not affect the delivery time or food preparation time. There is no bias in this regard. Customers are treated equally.
  • Some cuisines appear to be favorable amongst the customers as they were ordered more and given better ratings.
  • A Significant number of relatively cheaper cuisines received low ratings indicating customers did not give ratings based on the cost.

Recommendations:¶

  • To boost the number of orders on weekdays, special packages like discounts, free delivery, bonuses,etc. could be designed to encourage buying during this period.
  • To further confirm the distributions in the weekday and weekends, Foodhub can check for hoildays or special ceremonies in those periods as they could have impacted orders and not necessarily be a trend.
  • Traffic congestion and delivery availabilty could be reasons that impact delivery times on weekdays. More delivery routes could be explored to escape the congestion or faster modes of delivery could be employed. Also, more delivery agents could be employed to enhance faster delivery.
  • The uneven distribution of the different cuisines could be due to the the demograhy, food quality, branding, etc. Further investigation into these should be conducted to learn more.
  • A similar investigation should be made to learn more about the popularity of some restaurants compared to others.
  • A significant number of clients made an order only once. Foodhub can insist on feeback from such customers by reaching out directly. For consistent customers, rewards could be given to encourage them and stronger marketing and advertisement strategies developed to introduce more products to them.
  • Foodhub can reach out to customers who received orders without ratings to understand their reasons for doing so.
